  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: cd8f8ce2fb929114f841c9e41beb59b6, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ModuleContentController
  moduleImage: {fileID: 2088879001}
  descriptionText: {fileID: 1030546935}
  moduleImages:
  - {fileID: -6940281969297834453, guid: 5f51b38bf861c6c4da8e5e0ae93bf49e, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -4821259984463889197, guid: fcb8031dd827aa84d8ebe01384f94c66, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -5521222379383450511, guid: ee60a5c431c3fdc4a9a93afdcb0faef5, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 4846115073537997306, guid: fadba6bada9f45546ae1af8c65317e04, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 9186735890230495034, guid: c233217df0503d64b88627f5c05152a1, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -2828793657824102937, guid: 28c0aaf9446e67e4f9c5d66c0ef3c47f, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -8518524023266100217, guid: 759822bf89f5eea4d98adfc0e08d7256, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 2964964743579422540, guid: fb1814e3d832c7543a0879eed8c3afbc, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -8977564786713292925, guid: 29cf8e1fbaebc2245973778b64cd5e15, type: 3}
  - {fileID: -5941888252667042314, guid: 1cc82261c3ee3b54699479db4af4cf60, type: 3}
  descriptions:
  - "Meaning\r\nA Phillips screwdriver is a hand tool with a cross-shaped tip designed
    to fit screws with a \u201C+\u201D head. It is one of the most commonly used
    tools in computer assembly and repair.\r\nPurpose\r\nIts purpose is to tighten
    or loosen Phillips-head screws found in computer cases, motherboards, power supplies,
    and other hardware components.\r\nWhy This is Needed\r\nMost computer parts are
    secured using Phillips screws. Without this tool, it would be difficult or impossible
    to properly assemble or disassemble a computer system.\r\nUses\r\nRemoving and
    installing computer case screws\r\nOpening power supply units (PSU)\r\nSecuring
    motherboard and storage devices\r\nGeneral computer assembly and repair tasks\r\n"
  - 'Meaning

    A flat-head screwdriver is a tool with a straight, flat tip designed
    for screws with a single horizontal slot.

    Purpose

    It is used to loosen
    or tighten flat-head screws and sometimes for prying small components carefully.

    Why
    This is Needed

    Some older or specific computer parts still use flat-head
    screws. It is also useful for light prying tasks during disassembly.

    Uses

    Removing
    flat-head screws

    Opening tightly fitted computer panels (carefully)

    Assisting
    in minor adjustments

    Supporting general hardware repair

'
  - 'Meaning

    A hex or Allen wrench is a tool with a six-sided tip used to turn
    hexagonal screws and bolts.

    Purpose

    It is used to tighten or loosen
    hex screws commonly found in computer cases, racks, and mounting brackets.

    Why
    This is Needed

    Some computer cases and hardware use hex screws for stronger
    fastening, requiring this tool for proper handling.

    Uses

    Assembling
    computer cases

    Securing hardware brackets

    Tightening bolts in server
    racks

    Adjusting mounted components

'
  - 'Meaning

    Long nose pliers are hand tools with long, pointed jaws used for
    gripping small parts and reaching tight spaces.

    Purpose

    They are used
    to hold, bend, or pull small components inside a computer system.

    Why This
    is Needed

    Computer components are small and delicate. This tool helps technicians
    handle parts in narrow or hard-to-reach areas.

    Uses

    Pulling small screws
    or wires

    Bending cables or pins

    Holding components in tight spaces

    Assisting
    in cable management



'
  - 'Meaning

    Side cutting pliers are tools designed to cut wires and small cables
    cleanly.

    Purpose

    To cut electrical wires, cable ties, and connectors
    during installation or repair.

    Why This is Needed

    Proper cable cutting
    ensures clean installations and prevents messy or unsafe wiring inside a computer
    system.

    Uses

    Cutting cables and wires

    Removing zip ties

    Trimming
    excess wire length

    Supporting cable management

'
  - 'Meaning

    A wire stripper is a tool used to remove the protective insulation
    from electrical wires without damaging the metal inside.

    Purpose

    To
    prepare wires for connection, crimping, or installation.

    Why This is Needed

    Proper
    stripping ensures good electrical connection and prevents damage to the wire
    core.

    Uses

    Stripping network cables (LAN cables)

    Preparing wires
    for connectors

    Repairing damaged cables

    Electrical installations

'
  - 'Meaning

    A crimping tool is a device used to attach connectors to the ends
    of wires or cables by pressing them tightly together.

    Purpose

    To create
    strong and stable connections, especially for network cables like Ethernet.

    Why
    This is Needed

    Without proper crimping, cables may not work or may disconnect
    easily, causing network failure.

    Uses

    Attaching RJ45 connectors to
    LAN cables

    Building network cables

    Repairing broken connectors

    Installing
    network systems

'
  - 'Meaning

    Tweezers are small precision tools used to pick up or handle tiny
    components.

    Purpose

    To handle delicate or small parts that fingers
    cannot easily reach or grip.

    Why This is Needed

    Computer parts like
    jumpers, screws, or pins are very small and require precise handling.

    Uses

    Handling
    small screws or jumpers

    Placing tiny components

    Assisting in motherboard
    work

    Precision repair tasks

'
  - 'Meaning

    An anti-static wrist strap is a safety device worn on the wrist
    to prevent static electricity buildup.

    Purpose

    To protect sensitive
    computer components from electrostatic discharge (ESD) damage.

    Why This
    is Needed

    Static electricity from the human body can damage computer parts
    like RAM, CPU, and motherboard.

    Uses

    Preventing ESD damage

    Safely
    handling computer components

    Working inside computer systems

    Protecting
    sensitive electronics

'
  - 'Meaning

    A screw organizer or parts tray is a container used to store and
    organize screws and small components during repair or assembly.

    Purpose

    To
    prevent losing small parts and keep them organized during computer servicing.

    Why
    This is Needed

    Computer screws and parts are very small and easy to lose,
    which can delay repair or cause assembly errors.

    Uses

    Organizing screws
    and bolts

    Sorting computer parts

    Preventing loss of small components

    Improving
    repair efficiency

'
